  <article>
    <section xml:id="ps07-section">
      <title>Problem Set 7</title>

      <subtitle>Ordinary Differential Equations</subtitle>
      <xi:include href="ps01.ptx" xpointer="xpointer(//section[1]/introduction)" />
      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="ex-sep-variables-1">
          <statement>
            <p> Solve the differential equation <me>
                \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x+1}{y^2}
              </me>
              with the initial condition <m>y(0) = 3</m>. </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p> This is a separable differential equation. We can rearrange the equation to have all <m>
              y</m> terms on one side and all <m>x</m> terms on the other. <me>
                y^2 \,dy = (x+1) \,dx
              </me> Now,
              we integrate both sides: <me>
                \int y^2 \,dy = \int (x+1) \,dx
              </me>
                        <me>
              \frac{y^3}{3} = \frac{x^2}{2} + x + C
              </me>
              To solve for the constant <m>C</m>, we use the initial condition <m>y(0)=3</m>: <me>
              \frac{3^3}{3} = \frac{0^2}{2} + 0 + C
              </me>
                        <me>
              \frac{27}{3} = 0 + C \implies 9=C
              </me>
              The particular solution is: <me>
                \frac{y^3}{3} = \frac{x^2}{2} + x + 9
              </me>
              We can solve for <m>y</m> explicitly: <me>
                y^3 = \frac{3}{2}x^2 + 3x + 27
              </me>
                        <me>
              y = \sqrt[3]{\frac{3}{2}x^2 + 3x + 27}
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-sep-variables-2">
          <statement>
            <p> Solve the differential equation <m>y'(t) = ky</m>, where <m>y(0)=y_0</m>. This
              models exponential growth or decay. </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p> This is a separable differential equation. We can write <m>y'(t)</m> as <m>
              \frac{dy}{dt}</m>. <me>
                \frac{dy}{dt} = ky
              </me> Separate
              the variables: <me>
                \frac{1}{y} \,dy = k \,dt
              </me>
              Now, integrate both sides: <me>
                \int \frac{1}{y} \,dy = \int k \,dt
              </me>
                        <me>
              \ln|y| = kt + C
              </me>
              Exponentiate both sides to solve for <m>y</m>: <me>
                |y| = e^{kt+C} = e^{kt}e^C
              </me>
              Let <m>A = \pm e^C</m>. This allows us to remove the absolute value signs. <me>
                y(t) = Ae^{kt}
              </me> Now we use
              the initial condition <m>y(0)=y_0</m> to find <m>A</m>: <me>
                y_0 = A e^{k(0)} = A e^0 = A
              </me>
              So, <m>A=y_0</m>. The particular solution is: <me>
                y(t) = y_0 e^{kt}
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-sep-variables-3">
          <statement>
            <p> Solve the differential equation <me>
                \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{e^x}{y}
              </me>
              with the initial condition <m>y(0) = 1</m>. </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p> This is a separable differential equation. We separate the variables: <me>
                y \,dy = e^x \,dx
              </me> Integrate
              both sides: <me>
                \int y \,dy = \int e^x \,dx
              </me>
                        <me>
              \frac{y^2}{2} = e^x + C
              </me> Use
              the initial condition <m>y(0)=1</m> to find <m>C</m>: <me>
                \frac{1^2}{2} = e^0 + C
              </me>
                        <me>
              \frac{1}{2} = 1 + C \implies C = -\frac{1}{2}
              </me>
              The particular solution is: <me>
                \frac{y^2}{2} = e^x - \frac{1}{2}
              </me>
              We can solve for <m>y</m> explicitly: <me>
                y^2 = 2e^x - 1
              </me>
                        <me>
                y = \sqrt{2e^x - 1}
              </me> (We
              take the positive root since the initial condition gives a positive y value). </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-slope-field">
          <statement>
            <p> Match the differential equation with its slope field. <ol>
                <li>
                  <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = x+y
                  </me>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = xy
                  </me>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = y-1
                  </me>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
              <figure>
                <caption>Three different slope fields</caption>
              </figure>
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p> We analyze the behavior of each differential equation: <ol>
                <li> For <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = x+y
                  </me>,
              the slopes are constant along lines where <m>x+y=C</m>, or <m>y=-x+C</m>. This
              corresponds to a field with diagonal parallel isoclines. This matches **Slope Field
              B**. </li>

                <li> For <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = xy
                  </me>,
              the slope is 0 when either <m>x=0</m> or <m>y=0</m> (the x-axis and y-axis). This
              matches **Slope Field A**. </li>

                <li> For <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = y-1
                  </me>,
              the slope only depends on <m>y</m>. This means the slopes are constant along
              horizontal lines. This matches **Slope Field C**. </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>
